---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Compare', url: '/compare' },
  { name: 'BreederHQ vs EasyKeeper', url: '/compare/breederhq-vs-easykeeper' }
];

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is BreederHQ a good alternative to EasyKeeper for goat breeders?',
    answer: 'It depends on what part of your operation is under-served today. EasyKeeper is goats-only, web-only, and deep on herd operations (kidding, milk production, lactation, DHIR integration, health, tasks, reporting). EasyKeeper Essentials is $19/month or $209/year and Performance is $27/month or $297/year per easykeeper.com/plans-and-pricing, verified July 1, 2026. BreederHQ is a multi-species platform (goats plus 8 more species) with native iOS and Android apps, a transactional public marketplace, per-buyer client portal, per-litter and per-animal financial attribution, rules-based automation for offspring lifecycles, an embed widget that keeps your own website in sync, and Scout AI that reads lab PDFs and vet invoices into records. If dairy-goat DHIR is your center of gravity, EasyKeeper is the more specialized tool. If you run goats plus another species, or you want a marketplace and buyer flow attached to your operation, BreederHQ was built for that.'
  },
  {
    question: 'What does EasyKeeper cost vs BreederHQ?',
    answer: 'EasyKeeper Essentials is $19/month ($209/year annual). Performance is $27/month ($297/year annual). Both per easykeeper.com/plans-and-pricing on July 1, 2026. Trial is 30 days, no credit card required. BreederHQ pricing is on our pricing page. First 100 founding subscribers use code FOUNDER50 for 50% off Pro or Enterprise for 12 months.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Does EasyKeeper support species other than goats?',
    answer: 'No. EasyKeeper is explicitly a goat herd management platform. The homepage markets to "the modern goat breeder" and covers dairy, meat, fiber, and hobby/specialty goats. BreederHQ supports nine species in one account: dogs, cats, horses, goats, rabbits, sheep, alpacas, llamas, and cattle. If you run a mixed farm (goats plus LGDs, or goats plus sheep, or goats plus rabbits), that is one BreederHQ account, not two subscriptions.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Does EasyKeeper have a mobile app?',
    answer: 'EasyKeeper does not publicly advertise dedicated iOS or Android apps. The homepage states, "No download required. Access your records online at any time on an internet-connected device," indicating a web-app-only model with browser access from a phone. BreederHQ ships native iOS and Android apps in addition to the web app, scoped specifically for on-the-go capture (kidding pen, milking stand, pasture, feed store, vet visit).'
  },
  {
    question: 'Does BreederHQ support dairy production and DHIR the way EasyKeeper does?',
    answer: 'BreederHQ ships a mature dairy production surface today: milking records with butterfat, protein, SCC, MUN, and lactose; lactation cycles with dry-off; DHIA test-day recording with lab and certificate attachment; DHIA bulk CSV import with per-tenant mapping presets that make subsequent imports auto-match; Linear Appraisal (ADGA) with score, classification, four category scores, bulk CSV import, trend chart, and per-row public-visibility toggle for marketplace listings; peak yield tracking (peak daily production, date, days-to-peak, plus herd-level average peak and average days-to-peak); 305-day standardized lactation totals; a herd-level dashboard with lactation curves, top producers, mastitis-watch, and DHIA / appraisal rollups; and native iOS and Android mobile capture for milking, DHIA, and lactation start / dry-off. Where EasyKeeper still wins: age-adjusted 305-day lactation calc (BreederHQ ships a simplified 305-day calc without the age-adjustment factor), programmatic DHIR registry pull (BreederHQ is CSV-import only today), single-session batch milking capture UI (BreederHQ supports bulk import where each record carries its own timestamp, not a "milk 20 does at 6 AM in one session" workflow), and lactation persistence calculations. Where BreederHQ wins on dairy adjacencies: herd-level CAE / CL / Johne&apos;s status with private certificate binding; scrapie compliance (premises ID, structured tattoo placement, CVI, movement logs) as first-class rather than a notes field; FAMACHA, FEC, and FECRT as canonical trait entries with trend charts; native mobile capture; public marketplace listings that can surface production and appraisal data; per-buyer client portal; and the embed widget for a farm website. If your operation is dairy-goat-first and DHIR programmatic pull is core to your daily workflow, EasyKeeper is still the more specialized fit on those specific surfaces. If DHIA CSV import satisfies your test-day workflow and you also want the marketplace, buyer portal, mobile capture, and scrapie / herd-health surfaces, BreederHQ is competitive today, not "on roadmap."'
  },
  {
    question: 'Does EasyKeeper have a marketplace or a way to sell kids?',
    answer: 'EasyKeeper is a herd management platform and does not publicly market a buyer-facing marketplace or a per-buyer client portal for kid placements. BreederHQ runs a transactional marketplace at marketplace.breederhq.com where breeders publish listings for kids, breeding programs, and adult animals. When a kid is registered as born, a BreederHQ marketplace listing can be auto-generated from the program record. Sold kids drop from the listing automatically. If you sell kids off the farm, this is a real workflow difference.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I move my EasyKeeper records to BreederHQ?',
    answer: 'BreederHQ supports CSV import for animals, pedigrees, and contacts. Weight history, health events, and reproductive history can be imported if EasyKeeper provides CSV export. Photos and documents need re-upload. There is no one-click migration. Plan a few hours of setup or contact support@breederhq.com for scoping help. If EasyKeeper\'s export options are limited, raise that with their support before committing either direction. Data portability is a right, not a favor.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Is EasyKeeper a good product?',
    answer: 'Yes. EasyKeeper reports managing approximately 90,000 goats as of June 2026, has been in the market for years, and has a strong community reputation among dairy-goat breeders. If dairy goats are your center of gravity and DHIR is core to your operation, EasyKeeper is the specialist. This page is not a "we are better at everything" argument. It is the honest version of when each tool is the right pick.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Which is better for a mixed farm (goats + livestock guardian dogs + rabbits)?',
    answer: 'BreederHQ. One account, one subscription, one login, one mental model. Nine species supported in the same account. EasyKeeper is goats-only and would leave the dog and rabbit sides of the operation on a separate tool.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Which is better for a small dairy goat operation with no plans to expand species?',
    answer: 'Depends on which specific dairy surface matters most in the daily workflow. If age-adjusted 305-day lactation calc, programmatic DHIR registry pull, single-session batch milking capture UI, or lactation persistence calculations are core, EasyKeeper is the more specialized fit at $19 or $27 per month. If DHIA CSV import satisfies the test-day workflow (BreederHQ ships bulk CSV import with per-tenant mapping presets that auto-match on subsequent imports), peak-yield tracking is a shipped surface on BreederHQ (peak daily production, peak date, days-to-peak, plus herd-level averages), and you also want to sell kids through a public marketplace, run a client portal for kid buyers, auto-update your own farm website via the embed widget, capture in the milking parlor and kidding pen from a native mobile app, get first-class scrapie compliance and herd-level CAE / CL / Johne&apos;s status, or attribute expenses per doe and per kidding with quarterly tax export, BreederHQ is competitive on dairy today and adds surfaces EasyKeeper does not have. Both are legitimate. Which one wins for you depends on which specific dairy dimension is the daily-workflow bottleneck.'
  }
];

