    <section class="py-16 px-4">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-6">Where EasyKeeper genuinely wins</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">
          A comparison page that only lists where the other tool falls short is not honest. Here is where EasyKeeper is the better pick on its own terms, and why we recommend it in those cases.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-8">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">1. Specific dairy-production surfaces where EasyKeeper is more mature</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              BreederHQ ships milking records, lactation cycles, DHIA test-day recording, DHIA bulk CSV import with saved mapping presets, Linear Appraisal, peak-yield tracking (peak daily production, peak date, days-to-peak, plus herd-level averages), 305-day standardized totals, a herd dashboard with lactation curves and top producers, and native mobile capture. Where EasyKeeper is more mature today is on four specific surfaces: (a) age-adjusted 305-day lactation calculation (BreederHQ ships the 305-day calc but uses the simplified formula without age adjustment); (b) programmatic DHIR registry pull, discussed separately below; (c) single-session batch milking entry, where a breeder logs milk for many does in one timestamped session (BreederHQ supports bulk import where each record carries its own timestamp, which is the right tool for uploading a DHIA test-day CSV but not for the milk-stand rhythm of "weigh 20 does at 6 AM and enter it all at once"); (d) lactation persistence calculations (rate of decline from peak). On the milk-stand-first daily workflow with a Performance-tier dairy focus, EasyKeeper wins these four dimensions specifically. Everything else on dairy production is either tie or leans BreederHQ.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">2. DHIR programmatic registry pull</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              EasyKeeper advertises programmatic Dairy Herd Improvement Registry integration. For a dairy-goat operation enrolled in DHIR, that removes a category of data-entry work when test results come back from the processing center. BreederHQ&apos;s DHIA workflow is CSV-import based today: the processing center sends the CSV, the breeder uploads it, and BreederHQ&apos;s per-tenant mapping presets remember the header layout so subsequent imports auto-match. This is functional and low-friction on repeat, but it is not the same as a live registry pull. If a live pull is core to your workflow, this is a specialist EasyKeeper advantage.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">3. Community reputation among goat breeders</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              EasyKeeper has been in the goat-breeder community long enough to be a known quantity. ~90,000 goats are reportedly managed on the platform. New adopters can find peers who have run their program on EasyKeeper for years. That kind of peer-verified stability is worth something.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">4. Longer free trial</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              30 days versus BreederHQ&apos;s 14. If you want a full kidding season or a full lactation milestone to land inside your evaluation window, those extra 16 days matter. Both approaches are legitimate. EasyKeeper&apos;s longer runway is genuinely useful for evaluating dairy-specific workflows.
