    <!-- Where BreederHQ is different -->
    <section class="py-16 px-4 bg-gray-50">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-6">Where BreederHQ is a categorically different product</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">
          These are capability differences, not opinion. Each is sourced from publicly listed features on both vendors&apos; sites as of July 1, 2026.
        </p>

        <div class="space-y-8">
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">1. Nine species in one account</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              If you run goats plus a livestock guardian dog line, plus a small flock of hair sheep, plus a few rabbits, BreederHQ is one account with one subscription running the whole operation. EasyKeeper is goats-only, so the other species live somewhere else, on some other subscription, with some other login. Cross-species record-keeping, financial attribution, and reporting all fragment.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mt-3">
              For a homesteader-scale mixed farm or a serious multi-species operation, "one system for the whole operation" is a legitimate structural advantage that no goat-only tool can offer.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">2. Native iOS and Android mobile apps</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              EasyKeeper is web-only per their own homepage ("no download required, access from an internet-connected device"). BreederHQ ships a native Capacitor-based iOS and Android app deliberately scoped for the on-the-go breeder day. Enter weights in the kidding pen with one hand while holding a newborn. Photograph a kid with the built-in camera and attach it to the record on the spot. Record medications with withdrawal-period reminders while you are still at the pen. Snap a receipt from the feed store on the way out of the parking lot and Scout AI files the expense before you get home.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mt-3">
              This is not "responsive web that works on a phone." A browser open on your phone is not the same tool as a native app built for barn ergonomics. Both categories exist for good reasons, and if barn capture is a real constraint for your operation, note the difference.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">3. Transactional marketplace for kid sales</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              When you register a kidding on BreederHQ, marketplace listings for placement-eligible kids can be auto-generated from the program record. Sold kids drop from the listing when marked sold. Health testing done on the dam and sire surfaces on the kid&apos;s listing. Prospective buyers see the receipts (dam and sire genetics, CAE/CL status, ADGA registration status, weight-and-growth data) not just a marketing page. EasyKeeper does not publicly advertise a marketplace or a public buyer-discovery surface.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mt-3">
              For an operation that sells kids off the farm every season, this is one of the most consequential day-to-day workflow differences on the page.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">4. Per-buyer client portal</h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
              Each kid buyer gets their own login. They see their kid&apos;s records, photos, pedigree, contracts, invoices, direct messages, and documents. Deposits flow through Stripe to your bank account. Contracts are signed electronically. Photo updates go into the portal instead of a Facebook album that gets buried under new posts.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mt-3">
              This is the difference between "a buyer emails you asking for photos" and "the buyer opens their portal and sees a running record of everything about their kid." The client portal is what makes the transaction feel like a professional relationship, not a Facebook DM thread.
            </p>
          </div>

